1. Review Cyber-Security aspects related to the project
• Private MPLS from Liberia to Europe via MPLS and virtual routing and forwarding (VRF)
• Firewalls are compliant with standard architecture – Fortinet 200E at all sites (Buchanan, Tokadeh, 
Yekepa and Monrovia).
The proposed project is based on SD-WAN design used for the rest of the group. The design permits to create 
an efficient redundancy between Liberia and Europe to ensure the country will not be fully isolated for the 
rest of the group. The SD-WAN ONLY brings network connectivity to the Monrovia site.
The local deployment is using different modern technologies to distribute the access to different local sites 
(Buchanan, Tokadeh, Yekepa).
1.1 Risks on availability
• The Network design is to have primary via Fiber ring + Microwave communications inter-country. Backup 
will be provided via satellites at each of the three datacentres – Buchanan, Tokadeh and Yekepa. The VSAT 
will be redirected to connect to Europe WAN sites, this. technology should introduce latency and jitter in the 
different communications. This may negatively impact the voice and video traffic (IPBX, Teams, …). The 
proposed SLA on availabilities are not excellent.
• Multiple wireless links are proposed, this may lead to the same disturbances on the different services. 
However, The 4G/LTE is to provide access for Contractors (personal devices are not authorized to WIFI or 
GUEST network). In addition, it will be used for residential access to employees in a hierarchical mode (i.e. 
CEO, CFO, Managers, Heads of Departments etc). The LTE solution will replace the WiMAX solution 
completely.
• There are datacentres in Buchanan, Tokadeh and Yekepa that are interconnected without access to Monrovia. 
So, the three sites will be able to communicate amongst themselves. Monrovia is the primary jump off point 
to Europe, however, accommodation has been made to Abidjan (Cogent). Last resort is VSAT (7MB/3MB) 
to ensure connectivity to SAP systems in Brazil and other GWAN services. While VSAT is capable of 
running business critical apps such as SAP, the latency is not desirable, except for a short period of time. 
Mining Management have lived with this arrangement for the entire Marlink contract and continue to approve 
of this primary/secondary network. Due to the significant cost of communication networks in Liberia, local 
and global management are trying to balance cost vs. network primary/secondary configuration. The proposal is a like-for-like replacement of current terrestrial (microwave inter country + a growing fibber base) plus 
VSAT as backup. 
1.2 Risks on integrity
Based on currently used technology, the risk on data integrity of the network is very low and unlikely. It is 
unlikely to have some MITM equivalent attack on such design to modify the data integrity.
1.3 Risks on confidentiality
The SD-WAN design is built to bring security by design in the WAN, this design is helping to have more 
security. However, firewalls that are deployed on different sites are not part of SD-WAN design.
Whereas SD-WAN firewalls are managed by WAN team is their missions, management and responsibilities 
around local firewalls are not described. This may have impacts on consistency, and misunderstandings 
between teams and should lead to potential security issues.
The current roles and responsibilities are separated between network provider and Liberia IT Support. This 
will also be the case when contract is awarded to new provider. Part of the transition discussion is around 
roles and responsibilities.
1.4 Risks on Internet access
• In the proposed design, there is no possible DMZ design, whenever requested to expose some assets on the 
Internet, it will mandatory to install a dedicated Internet access to expose the service on the Internet. This 
could lead to a security risk for the rest of the local network. This information is not communicated in the 
document. However, there is no current business need for a DMZ in Liberia at this point in time. In the event 
a business system requires a DMZ, the work will need to be treated as a project between IT Liberia and 
network provider (where necessary). Liberia uses Azure for Windows based development and SAP for all 
major business systems.
• Internet break-out will be done via Monrovia Fibber, and backup on another site are using microwave to 
Monrovia. This may lead to Internet access failure.
1.5 Sabotage / Incident
As a large part of the network will use LTE technology, we may face to connexion issues based on 4G 
availability / perturbations. There is no precision on antenna unavailability due to sabotage, on-purpose waves 
perturbation, or accidental antenna disruption.
The LTE portion of the network is to support the residential (quality of life) and Contractor base. While 
important, it isn’t as critical a priority as the identified business network. Orange has built two-30 metre 
towers at no expense– one in Buchanan (HQ) and one near the Gangra mine. This infrastructure is there to 
support Orange growth in Liberia. Sabotage and theft are on-going concerns in Liberia. As a result, the areas 
housing the towers are staffed by 24/7 security personnel. Staff are in place to mitigate risk while balancing 
costs

