FLORIAN HOEFNER: PIANIST / COMPOSER / RECORDING ARTIST

Florian Hoefner is a Juno winning jazz pianist and composer who has established himself as a prominent voice in contemporary jazz. Born and raised in Germany, Hoefner received his musical training in New York City and has since become a resident of Canada. He draws from a diverse range of influences to create a unique brand of jazz that has garnered critical acclaim. Hoefner's latest album, "First Spring," was released in September 2019 and features his arrangements of folk tunes from around the world alongside new original compositions. The album was nominated for a 2021 Juno Award and won "Instrumental Recording of the Year" and "Jazz Recording of the Year" at the 2020 East Coast Music Awards.

In addition to his work as a solo artist, Hoefner is also the leader of the Florian Hoefner Group, a quartet that has released three albums and toured extensively across North America, Europe, and Australia. The group has received glowing reviews and has been recognized with awards such as the Stingray Rising Star Award after their performance at the Montréal Jazz Festival. Hoefner has also released several albums as a member of the Germany-based collective, Subtone, and has collaborated with many prominent musicians.

Hoefner is a two-time winner of the ASCAP Young Jazz Composer Award, and his big band compositions have been performed by the New York Jazz Orchestra, the Lucerne Jazz Orchestra, and more. He received a Fulbright Scholarship to complete his Master of Music degree from the Manhattan School of Music and has studied with Jason Moran, Dave Liebman, and Garry Dial. Currently, he serves as Assistant Professor for Jazz Studies at Memorial University in St. John's, Newfoundland, Canada.

